  {
    "type": "EXEGETICAL (ORIGINAL LANGUAGES)",
    "name": "Pulpit Commentary",
    "elements": [
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "cmt_sub_title",
        "text": "Verse 37.",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " - ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "cmt_word",
        "text": "Which departed not from the temple, but served God with fastings and prayers night and day",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ". Probably, in virtue of her reputation as a prophetess, some small chamber in the temple was assigned to her. This seems to have been the case with Huldah (",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "2 Chronicles 34:22",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "). It has also been suggested that she lovingly performed some work in or about the sacred building. Farrar suggests such as trimming the lamps (as is the rabbinic notion about Deborah), derived from the word lapidoth, splendor. Such sacred functions were regarded among all nations as a high honor. The great city of Ephesus boasted her name of ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "greek",
        "text": "νεωκόρος",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ", temple-sweeper, as her proudest title to honor. Luke 2:37",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "",
        "children": []
      }
    ]
  },
  {
    "type": "EXEGETICAL (ORIGINAL LANGUAGES)",
    "name": "Vincent's Word Studies",
    "elements": [
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "Of about fourscore and four years (ὡς ἐτῶν ὀγδοήκοντα τεσσάρων)",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "p",
        "class": "",
        "text": "The A. V. might be supposed to be stating her age; but the best texts read ἕως, until, instead of ὡς about; and the statement refers to the time of her widowhood; a widow even for (or up to) fourscore and four years. So Rev.",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "p",
        "class": "",
        "text": "Served (λατρεύουσα)",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "p",
        "class": "",
        "text": "The present participle, serving. Rev., worshipping. See on Luke 1:74. ",
        "children": [
          {
            "element": "span",
            "class": "",
            "text": "The present participle, serving. Rev., worshipping. See on ",
            "children": []
          },
          {
            "element": "span",
            "class": "verse-link",
            "text": "Luke 1:74",
            "children": []
          },
          {
            "element": "span",
            "class": "",
            "text": ". ",
            "children": []
          }
        ]
      }
    ]
  }
